'''Paul Beck Goddard''' (1811 - July 5, 1866) was an American physician and editor of medical books who also made pioneering contributions to [[photography]].{{r|e19cp}}

He graduated from the medical school of the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1832. As well as practicing as a physician and surgeon, he was professor of anatomy at [[Franklin Medical College]] of Philadelphia,
and a member of the [[American Philosophical Society]].{{r|e19cp}}

In his experimental photography work with [[Robert Cornelius]], in 1839<ref name="Barger2000">{{Cite book |last=Barger |first=M. Susan |last2=White |first2=William B. |year=2000 |orig-year=First published 1991 |title=The Daguerreotype: Nineteenth-Century Technology and Modern Science |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FLTyvuWX6MMC&pg=PA33 |publisher=JHU Press |pages=33–34 |isbn=978-0-8018-6458-2 |language=en}}</ref> Goddard became the first to use [[bromide]] for [[daguerreotype]]s. Goddard was then working as an assistant to University of Pennsylvania Chemistry professor Dr. Robert Hare, and this chemistry background contributed to his successful experiments with bromine.<ref name="Barger2000" /> Recognizing the potential of this innovation, which significantly decreased exposure times,<ref name="Barger2000" /> Goddard helped Cornelius set up a commercial photography studio.{{r|e19cp}}

Goddard died in Philadelphia on July 5, 1866. Reporting his death, ''[[The New York Times]]'' described him "one of the most eminent physicians of this country" and said, "His devotion to wounded soldiers during the war gained him great popularity among the people."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nyti.ms/2usTfdH|title=Death of Dr. Paul Beck Goddard.|last=|first=|date=July 6, 1866|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-30|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref>

