{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Traveller'' (poem)}}
'''''The Traveller; or, a Prospect of Society''''' (1764) is a philosophical poem by [[Oliver Goldsmith]].  In [[heroic verse]] of an [[Augustan poetry|Augustan]] style it discusses the causes of happiness and unhappiness in nations.  It was the work which first made Goldsmith’s name, and is still considered a classic of mid-18th century poetry.

== Synopsis ==

The dedication to ''The Traveller'' sets out Goldsmith's purpose:
<blockquote>I have attempted to show, that there may be equal happiness in states, that are differently governed from our own; that every state has a particular principle of happiness, and that this principle in each may be carried to a mischievous excess.</blockquote>
He begins the poem by extolling the happiness of his brother Henry's simple family life.  Then, from a vantage-point in the [[Alps]], he surveys the condition of the world.  Every nation, he says, considers itself the happiest, but this is only because each nation judges by its own standards.  In fact, happiness is probably equally spread, though in different forms which tend to be mutually exclusive.
<blockquote>From Art more various are the blessings sent;<br/>Wealth, commerce, honour, liberty, content.<br/>Yet these each other's power so strong contest,<br/>That either seems destructive of the rest.<br/>Where wealth and freedom reign, contentment fails,<br/>And honour sinks where commerce long prevails.<ref>Line 87</ref></blockquote>
Then Goldsmith turns to consider various countries individually.  [[Italy]] is naturally fertile and was formerly successful in commerce, but has since been overtaken by other countries.  The remaining great works of art and architecture only inspire a childish love of show in the Italians.  [[Swiss people|The Swiss]] have poverty, but also equality.  They love home-life and simple things, but have no nobility of soul.  [[France]] is a nation motivated by honour, and is therefore too prone to vanity.  In [[Netherlands|Holland]] industry has brought prosperity, but
<blockquote>E'en liberty itself is barter'd here.<br/>At gold's superior charms all freedom flies,<br />The needy sell it, and the rich man buys.<ref>Line 306</ref></blockquote>
Britain's free constitution has led to a lack of social cohesion, the rich defending their own liberties by oppressing the poor.  Those who have escaped this problem by fleeing across the Atlantic have found a harsh and dangerous land in America.  The poem concludes with the thought that happiness lies within:
<blockquote>How small, of all that human hearts endure,<br/>That part which laws or kings can cause or cure.<br/>Still to ourselves in every place consign'd,<br/>Our own felicity we make or find.<ref>Line 429</ref></blockquote>

== Composition ==

Goldsmith began writing ''The Traveller'' in 1755 while he was travelling in [[Switzerland]].  His travels in Europe in that and the following year gave him much material to draw on, but he seems to have let the poem drop.  He resumed it in 1763, by which time he was living at Canonbury House in [[Islington]], and completed it in 1764.  Most of the last few lines of the poem was contributed by Goldsmith's friend [[Samuel Johnson|Dr. Johnson]].{{sfn|Sells|1974|pp=288–289}}<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Dinah |editor1-last=Birch |editor1-link=Dinah Birch |editor2-first=Katy |editor2-last=Hooper |title=The Concise Oxford Companion to English Literature |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tc_YWBwCuyYC&pg=PA725&lpg=PA725&dq=%22recalled+from+Goldsmith%27s+own+continental+tour%22&source=bl&ots=tgCnxzZO1q&sig=j-bHszq6vXd_18TTeoulpRTQRR8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Mjg_Uu_BGufJ0wWUrYD4Ag&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22recalled%20from%20Goldsmith%27s%20own%20continental%20tour%22&f=false |accessdate=22 September 2013 |edition=4th |year=2012 |origyear=1990 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=9780199608218 |page=725 }}</ref>  Goldsmith chose not to dedicate ''The Traveller'' to some powerful or wealthy patron, as was the normal practice of the time, but to his brother Henry, the ill-paid curate of an Irish parish.{{sfn|Dussinger|2004–2013}}

== Publication ==

''The Traveller'' was first published on 19 December 1764 by [[John Newbery]], though the year was given on the imprint as 1765.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=David |editor1-last=Masson |editor1-link=David Masson |title=The Miscellaneous Works of Oliver Goldsmith |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4D4CAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR37&dq=%22one+shilling+and+sixpence+with+this+title%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yPE1Up3BEcyU7Qa6gIH4DA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22one%20shilling%20and%20sixpence%20with%20this%20title%22&f=false |accessdate=22 September 2013 |year=1869 |publisher=Macmillan |location=London |page=xxxvii }}</ref>{{sfn|Prior|1837|p=25}}  It was the first of Goldsmith's books to feature his name on the title-page.{{sfn|Ford|1977|p=380}}  Goldsmith received only £21 for ''The Traveller'', but the publisher must have made a good deal more, since a second edition appeared in March 1765, a fourth in August 1765 (only eight months after the first), and a ninth before Goldsmith's death in 1774.  The author continued to revise the poem for the rest of his life, so that the ninth edition contained 36 new lines not in the first.{{sfn|Prior|1837|pp=42–46, 56–58}}

== Sources ==

The style of ''The Traveller'' stands in the tradition of verse in [[heroic couplet]]s that had dominated English poetry for the previous hundred years.  In particular, it owes a debt to [[John Dryden|Dryden]] and [[Alexander Pope|Pope]], to whose poems it has often been favourably compared.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Walter |editor1-last=M'Leod |title=Goldsmith's Traveller |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C8ITAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA16&dq=%22heroic+verse%22+%22the+traveller%22+goldsmith&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xo1BUqvXE-rE7Abcn4CgBA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22heroic%20verse%22%20%22the%20traveller%22%20goldsmith&f=false |accessdate=27 September 2013 |year=1865 |publisher=Longman, Green, Longman, Roberts & Green |location=London |page=16 }}</ref>{{sfn|Ross|1971|p=217}}{{sfn|Bohn|1845|p=70}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Aikin |first1=J. |authorlink1=John Aikin |title=Letters to a Young Lady on a Course of English Poetry |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xkoJAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA264&dq=%22the+traveller%22+goldsmith+dryden+pope&hl=en&sa=X&ei=yOU-UqjIMKmJ0AXBPA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwATgU#v=onepage&q=%22the%20traveller%22%20goldsmith%20dryden%20pope&f=false |accessdate=22 September 2013 |year=1807 |publisher=J. Johnson |location=London |page=264 }}</ref>

From an early date much attention has been paid to Goldsmith’s sources for the plan and subject-matter of the poem.  Many who knew Goldsmith personally, having no great opinion of his abilities, believed that ''The Traveller'' owed much to the conversation of Dr. Johnson, as may well be the case, or even that Johnson had written a substantial part of it for him.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Irving |first1=Washington |authorlink1=Washington Irving |title=Works. Volume 11: Oliver Goldsmith |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gP5DAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA162&dq=%22such+magic+numbers+had+flowed%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JPA_UtS6MKPS0QXtuYC4Bw&ved=0CGkQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22such%20magic%20numbers%20had%20flowed%22&f=false |accessdate=23 September 2013 |year=1849 |publisher=George P. Putnam |location=New York |pages=162–163 }}</ref>{{sfn|Forster|1855|pp=210–211}}  [[Joseph Addison]]'s ''Letters from Italy'' has a rather similar theme, insofar as it is a piece of travel-writing describing the Italian landscape and character in verse.{{sfn|Prior|1837|pp=26–27}}  Other names that have been mentioned include [[Richard Blackmore]]'s ''The Nature of Man'', [[James Thomson (poet)|James Thomson]]'s ''Liberty'', and [[Thomas Gray]]'s fragment on "The Alliance of Education and Government".<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Frederick |editor1-last=Tupper |title=Goldsmith's The Traveller and The Deserted Village |url=https://archive.org/stream/goldsmithstravel00gold#page/22/mode/2up |accessdate=23 September 2013 |year=1900 |publisher=Silver, Burdett |location=New York |pages=23–24 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Poetical Works of Oliver Goldsmith |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=84U-AAAAYAAJ&pg=PR61&dq=%22Brydges+%28venerabile+nomen%29%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Luc9UqWSI8G50QWhzYGYCA&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Brydges%20%28venerabile%20nomen%29%22&f=false |accessdate=23 September 2013 |year=1855 |publisher=William Pickering |location=London |page=lxi }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Arnold |first1=Matthew |authorlink1=Matthew Arnold |editor1-first=R. H. |editor1-last=Super |title=English Literature and Irish Politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HjauqIIr16IC&pg=PA202&dq=%22Traveller,+and+indeed+in+the+poem+on+The+Alliance%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_Oo-UtKgD6Gf0QWc9YGoAg&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Traveller%2C%20and%20indeed%20in%20the%20poem%20on%20The%20Alliance%22&f=false |accessdate=23 September 2013| series=Complete Prose Works, Volume 9 |year=1973 |publisher=University of Michigan Press |location=Ann Arbor |isbn=0472116592 |pages=202–203 }}</ref>  There are also one or two verbal resemblances to [[Samuel Garth]]'s "Claremont" and [[Matthew Prior]]'s "Written at Paris in the Beginning of Robe's Geography".{{sfn|Prior|1837|pp=49–50}}  More recent research has shown that the philosophy of ''The Traveller'' owes much to [[Georges-Louis Leclerc, Comte de Buffon|Buffon]]'s ''Histoire naturelle'' and [[Montesquieu]]'s ''Esprit des lois''.{{sfn|Sells|1974|pp=288–289}}

== Critical reception ==

''The Traveller'' was the poem which made Goldsmith's reputation.{{sfn|Ford|1977|p=380}}{{sfn|Dussinger|2004–2013}}  Dr. Johnson, so [[James Boswell|Boswell]] reports, said that "there had not been so fine a poem since Pope's time", and he went on to write a brief but laudatory article on it in the ''[[The Critical Review|Critical Review]]''.{{sfn|Forster|1855|p=210}}{{sfn|Prior|1837|p=34}}  Two months after publication the ''St. James's Chronicle'' praised "the beauties of this poem" as "great and various",{{sfn|Forster|1855|pp=213–214}} and this opinion was seconded by the ''[[The Gentleman's Magazine|Gentleman's Magazine]]'' and in large measure by the ''[[Monthly Review (London)|Monthly Review]]'', though the ''Monthly''’s reviewer also took Goldsmith to task for his [[Tory (British political party)|Tory]] suspicion of commerce.{{sfn|Prior|1837|p=35}}{{sfn|Dussinger|2004–2013}}  Readers of all ages soon began to discover ''The Traveller''’s merits.  The 17-year-old [[Charles James Fox]] admired the poem; a few years later the even younger [[William Wordsworth]] read ''The Traveller'', and was influenced by it when he wrote his earliest surviving poem, "Lines Written as a School Exercise".{{sfn|Forster|1855|p=213}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wu |first1=Duncan |authorlink1=Duncan Wu |title=Wordsworth's Reading 1770–1799 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y6_Ou68RnNQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate=23 September 2013 |year=1994 |origyear=1993 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge  |isbn=0521416000 |page=69 }}</ref>  The poem's critical reception continued high, though it often suffered by comparison with his ''The Deserted Village''.  The bibliographer [[Samuel Egerton Brydges|Egerton Brydges]] preferred ''The Traveller'':
<blockquote>The sentiments are always interesting, generally just, and often new; the imagery is elegant, picturesque, and occasionally sublime; the language is nervous, highly finished, and full of harmony.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Allibone |first1=S. Austin |authorlink1=Samuel Austin Allibone |title=A Critical Dictionary of English Literature. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WmILAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA695&dq=%22The+sentiments+are+always+interesting,+generally+%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Q-8-Uri8B4bR0QXL64HIBQ&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22The%20sentiments%20are%20always%20interesting%2C%20generally%20%22&f=false |accessdate=23 September 2013 |year=1858 |publisher=Childs & Peterson |location=Philadelphia |page=695 }}</ref></blockquote>
But many followed the poets [[Thomas Campbell (poet)|Thomas Campbell]] and [[Leigh Hunt]] in rating ''The Deserted Village'' higher.  Campbell said ''The Traveller''’s field of contemplation was rather desultory, while Hunt complained that some feeble lines gave it the air of having been [[Interpolation (manuscripts)|interpolated]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Walter |title=Biographical Memoirs of Eminent Novelists, and Other Distinguished Persons. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c5ELAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA249&dq=%22The+field+of+contemplation+in+the+Traveller%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=CfE-UpnkEofI0AW9w4CgDQ&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22The%20field%20of%20contemplation%20in%20the%20Traveller%22&f=false |accessdate=27 September 2013 |series=The Miscellaneous Prose Works of Sir Walter Scott, Bart. Volume 3 |year=1834 |publisher=Robert Cadell |location=Edinburgh |page=249 }}</ref>{{sfn|Rousseau|1974|p=315}}  The publisher [[Henry George Bohn|Henry Bohn]] claimed that ''The Traveller'' "combines the highest beauties of ethic and descriptive poetry."<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Henry G. |editor1-last=Bohn |title=The Works of Oliver Goldsmith, with a Life and Notes. Volume 1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6igvAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA70&dq=%22short+of+his+master+it+must+be+admitted%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7Ug_UsCBJKeH0AX-pID4Ag&ved=0CEkQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22short%20of%20his%20master%20it%20must%20be%20admitted%22&f=false |accessdate=27 September 2013 |year=1845 |publisher=Henry G. Bohn |location=London |page=70 }}</ref>  [[Thomas Babington Macaulay, 1st Baron Macaulay|Lord Macaulay]]'s opinion was that
<blockquote>In general [Goldsmith's] designs were bad, and his execution good.  In ''The Traveller'', the execution, though deserving of much praise, is far inferior to the design.  No philosophical poem, ancient or modern, has a plan so noble, and at the same time so simple.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Edmund |editor1-last=Fuller |editor1-link=Edmund Fuller |title=The Great English and American Essays |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nezXAAAAMAAJ&q=%22designs+were+bad,+and+his+execution%22&dq=%22designs+were+bad,+and+his+execution%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=C_M-UpqICMiY0QXV14CwAw&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAzgK |accessdate=27 September 2013 |year=1964 |publisher=Avon |location=New York |page=141 }}</ref></blockquote>
The novelist [[William Black (novelist)|William Black]], on the other hand, while highly praising the poem's mellifluous qualities, admitted that "the literary charm of ''The Traveller'' is more apparent than the value of any doctrine, however profound or ingenious, which the poem was supposed to inculcate".<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goldsmith |first1=Oliver |title=The Vicar of Wakefield, The Traveller, The Deserted Village |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ur5EAAAAYAAJ&q=%22more+apparent+than+the+value+of+any%22&dq=%22more+apparent+than+the+value+of+any%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=5_M-UuP9KIXG0QXF74HwAg&ved=0CE0Q6AEwBg |accessdate=27 September 2013 |year=1905 |publisher=[[A. L. Burt]] |location=New York |page=61 }}</ref>  More recent academic criticism continues to assert the poem's claims to respectful attention.  Arthur Humphreys considered it "a true and thoughtful poem";<ref>{{cite book |last1=Humphreys |first1=A. L. |editor1-first=Boris |editor1-last=Ford |title=From Dryden to Johnson |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CAseAAAAIAAJ&q=%22true+and+thoughtful+poem%22&dq=%22true+and+thoughtful+poem%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-F5FUuTaDMOx0AWmkYCABA&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ |accessdate=27 September 2013 |series=The Pelican Guide to English Literature, Volume 4 |year=1977 |origyear=1957 |publisher=Penguin |location=Harmondsworth |page=87 |chapter=The Literary Scene }}</ref> [[Boris Ford]] noted "the judicious tone, the unruffled movement, the urbane and fluent control of the couplet", which "established him as a great Augustan poet";{{sfn|Ford|1977|p=380}} and Angus Ross thought that ''The Traveller'' proved him a poet with an individual voice, citing particularly its "genuine and deep note of feeling".{{sfn|Ross|1971|p=217}}

