'''Yangmingism''', known in [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]] as ''Yángmíngxué'' (陽明學) and in Japanese as ''Yōmeigaku''<ref name="craig2">{{citation |last=Craig|first=Edward |title=Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Volume 7 |year=1998 |publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-07310-3}}</ref> (陽明学), is one of the major philosophical schools of [[Neo-Confucianism]], based on the ideas of the Neo-Confucian philosopher [[Wang Yangming]]. Yangmingism developed as the main intellectual opposition to the [[Cheng-Zhu school]] of [[Neo-Confucianism]].<ref name="mote1">{{citation |last=Mote|first=Frederick W. |title=Imperial China 900-1800  |year=2003 |publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-01212-7}}</ref> The school is considered part of the [[School of Mind]], established by [[Lu Jiuyuan]]. Yangmingism emphasizes that, one can get the supreme principle (理) from his/her heart, without seeking outside. Futhermore, Yangmingism posits a oneness of [[Action (philosophy)|action]] and knowledge in relation to one's concepts of morality. In essence, this is the idea that one's conceptualization of good and evil are irrelevant if one does not, in reality, act in accordance with that conceptualization: "to know and not to act is not to know". Naturally, this extended to the political sphere, and, through incorporation into [[Mitogaku]] thought, a violent form of Yangmingism became an influence on the incipient [[Sonno-joi|anti-foreigner]] movement in 19th century Japan.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ravina |first1=Mark |title=The Last Samurai : The Life and Battles of Saigō Takamori |date=2005 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9780471705376}}</ref> In the 20th century, Japanese author and nationalist [[Yukio Mishima]] examined Yangmingism as an integral part of the ideologies behind the [[Meiji Restoration]] as well as further samurai resistance, in particular the [[Shinpūren rebellion]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mishima |first1=Yukio |title=Kōdōgaku Nyūmon |date=1970 |publisher=Bungei Shunjū}}</ref>

